    "text": "yeah I am hoping the reactive runtime gives it an uber-tight feedback loop. The feedback is the environment, not the training data. I often see the agent initially cannot call its own tools properly at first, but after round 10 it is warmed up and very productive. The early failures are because I have not optimized the prompt yet, its often completely out-of-whack with what I have actually implemented, but also, I don't really need to, coz the environment is the strong feedback signal.\n\nYes its also pretty bad at overall architecture, but it is *great* at copying established patterns. Robocoop3 itself is so much better than my previous LLM project, written in a tenth of the time coz I figured out how to get it it to port the agent loop from OpenCode.\n\nMost of my prompts are: Look at X, Y Z, now do it in C. Usually X, Y and Z is something I wrote a few years ago. OpenCode port was the first time I ported 3rd party code, its MIT licensed and I attribute it. I think that unblocks a ton of options of remixing. So unless every aspect of a project is totally rethought from the ground up, I think you can actually very easily make a game if you have a game that has somewhat the right architecture in place.\n\nits gonna insane in another year's time",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1769971142.056149",
    "parent_user_id": "U02E4DAQGSZ",
